Setup
  1. Have Kali Linux, virtualbox, and the EmpireBreakout virtual machine downloaded 
  2. make sure all aspects are extracted and visible to Virtualbox
  3. In files: import appliance, select the Empire Breakout virtual machine
  4. in tools: create a NAT network and connect the 2 virtual machines to it

evaluation:
    Empire Breakout is a beginner-friendly CTF machine focused on enumeration, source code analysis, and credential discovery. The attack chain involves web reconnaissance, Samba enumeration, and decoding an obfuscated password hidden in plain sight.

Reconnaissance:
    Port Scan
    nmap -sV -sC -oN scan.txt 10.0.2.4
    PortServiceVersion80HTTPApache 2.4.51 (Debian)139NetBIOSSamba smbd 4445SMBSamba smbd 410000HTTPWebmin 1.98120000HTTPUsermin 1.830
    Five open ports were identified. Ports 10000 and 20000 run Webmin and Usermin respectively, both served over HTTPS with self-signed certificates, this causes a expected behaviour that produces a browser security warning, but its not a dead end.

Web Enumeration — Port 80
    gobuster dir -u http://10.0.2.4 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt
    PathStatus.htpasswd403.htaccess403.hta403index.html200manual/301server-status403
    The 403 results confirm those files exist but are protected by Apache. No directly exploitable paths were found at this stage.

Source Code Analysis:
Manual inspection of the Apache default page source revealed a hidden comment hidden at the bottom containing the semi encrypted string:
don't worry no one will get here, it's safe to share with you my access. Its encrypted :)
++++++++++[>+>+++>+++++++>++++++++++<<<<-]>>++++++++++++++++.++++.>>+++++++++++++++++.
----.<++++++++++.-----------.>-----------.++++.<<+.>-.--------.++++++++++++++++++++.
<------------.>>---------.<<++++++.++++++.
The string was initially suspected to be a hash, but hashid and hash-identifier returned no matches. Further research identified it as Brainfuck (odd programming language) not actually an encryption scheme.

Decoding:
    Decoded using dcode.fr/brainfuck-language:
    the result was .2uqPEfj3D<P'a-3

Samba Enumeration:
enum4linux -a 10.0.2.4 :
    Hostname = BREAKOUT
    Domain = WORKGROUP
    Samba version = 4.13.5-Debian
Shares:
    ShareAccessprint$DeniedIPC$Null session only
    User discovered via RID cycling:
    S-1-22-1-1000 Unix User\cyber (Local User)
The enum4linux output contains three categories of users worth distinguishing:
    1. Known Usernames (administrator, guest, root, etc.) = these are hardcoded default guesses built into enum4linux, not actually confirmed accounts on the target.
       nobody = a reserved default system account present on all Linux machines. It has no login shell and is not usable for authentication.
       cyber = confirmed via RID cycling with RID 1000. On Debian/Linux systems, UID 1000 is assigned to the first human-created user account, meaning this was deliberately set up on the machine and is login-capable.
    2. Password policy (no lockout) and a minimum password length of 5
    4. Account lockout threshold = None brute force is possible without risk of lockout

Privilege escalation:
    With a confirmed username from Samba enumeration and a decoded password from the page source, credentials were tested against Usermin (port 20000) as the most appropriate target for a standard user account.
    FieldValueUsernamecyberPassword.2uqPEfj3D<P'a-3Targethttps://10.0.2.4:20000
    Login was successful.

Flag Capture:
    Access to Usermin provided a command shell interface. Navigation through the user's home directory revealed user.txt, containing the user flag.

Key Takeaways:
    Always review page source manually — automated scanners cannot read content within pages, only discover paths.
    Brainfuck and other esoteric languages will not be identified by hash tools. When identification fails, research the character set.
    RID cycling via enum4linux can confirm real user accounts even when share access is denied.
    SSL warnings on CTF machines are expected — self-signed certificates are standard for services like Webmin/Usermin and should not be treated as dead ends.
    UID 1000 on Linux systems reliably indicates the first human-created user account.
    Automated hash identification tools will not recognise esoteric language encodings. Manual research is essential when tools return no results.

